1
00:00:21,388 --> 00:00:23,151
Hey, hey, hey,
hey, slow it down.

2
00:00:27,827 --> 00:00:29,658
Dear Mr. And Mrs. Andrews.

3
00:00:29,729 --> 00:00:31,492
Mr. And Mrs. Baldwin.

4
00:00:31,564 --> 00:00:33,532
Dear Lieutenant
and Mrs. Franks.

5
00:00:33,600 --> 00:00:35,261
Dear Mr. And Mrs. Peterson.

6
00:00:35,335 --> 00:00:37,394
Dear Mr. And Mrs. Lupo.

7
00:00:37,470 --> 00:00:40,462
I'm sure you've never received
a letter of this nature before,

8
00:00:40,540 --> 00:00:42,303
and I'm also quite sure
you'll be surprised

9
00:00:42,375 --> 00:00:45,640
by the circumstances
under which I'm writing it.

10
00:00:45,712 --> 00:00:48,476
My name is Alex Chivescu,
and I'm a junior,

11
00:00:48,548 --> 00:00:51,039
soon to be a senior at
Eagle Creek High School

12
00:00:51,117 --> 00:00:52,584
in Rochester Hills.

13
00:00:58,224 --> 00:01:01,455
My parents moved to Michigan
to go to college here,

14
00:01:01,528 --> 00:01:03,018
they divorced when
I was two years old

15
00:01:03,096 --> 00:01:06,065
and I have not heard
from my father since.

16
00:01:06,132 --> 00:01:08,293
My mother is a nurturing
and caring person

17
00:01:08,368 --> 00:01:11,826
who inspired my love
of learning.

18
00:01:11,905 --> 00:01:13,668
This paper says
you're a doctor.

19
00:01:13,740 --> 00:01:15,833
Well, sort of.

20
00:01:15,909 --> 00:01:18,070
This is more
than a piece of paper, Alex,

21
00:01:18,144 --> 00:01:20,009
this is why I came
to this country.

22
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:21,843
It's why I've studied
so hard.

23
00:01:21,915 --> 00:01:25,282
Education is like a magic key
to open any door.

24
00:01:25,351 --> 00:01:27,945
With it, anything is possible.

25
00:01:28,021 --> 00:01:31,047
Can I go to a school
like this someday too?

26
00:01:31,124 --> 00:01:33,957
Absolutely, absolutely.

27
00:01:34,027 --> 00:01:38,555
Your education is going
to be even better than mine.

28
00:01:38,631 --> 00:01:42,761
You'll go to a great university
like... Harvard.

29
00:01:42,836 --> 00:01:44,326
Is Harvard the best?

30
00:01:44,404 --> 00:01:45,871
The very best.

31
00:01:45,939 --> 00:01:47,372
Then that's where I'll go.

32
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:48,498
You'll have to work hard.

33
00:01:48,575 --> 00:01:50,634
I will, I promise.

34
00:01:50,710 --> 00:01:53,178
You'll see.

35
00:01:53,246 --> 00:01:54,804
You make me so proud.

36
00:01:56,716 --> 00:01:58,377
So proud.

37
00:02:17,370 --> 00:02:19,361
Perfect,
what do you think?

38
00:02:19,439 --> 00:02:21,407
I think I want one too.

39
00:02:21,474 --> 00:02:23,704
You can get a head
start on that.

40
00:02:23,776 --> 00:02:25,801
You do your homework
while I make us some dinner.

41
00:02:25,879 --> 00:02:28,478
Okay.

42
00:02:30,517 --> 00:02:31,506
You hungry?

43
00:02:31,584 --> 00:02:32,744
Yes, I'm starving.

44
00:02:32,819 --> 00:02:33,979
Good.

45
00:02:45,498 --> 00:02:48,296
Um, my teacher said you wanted
to see me, Mrs. Thomas?

46
00:02:48,368 --> 00:02:51,166
Yes, Alex, you know your
mother's friend Miss Carson?

47
00:02:51,237 --> 00:02:52,169
Hi, Miss Carson.

48
00:02:52,238 --> 00:02:54,399
Hi, Alex, why don't
you have a seat?

49
00:03:00,713 --> 00:03:07,414
Alex, I'm sorry to have to be
the one to tell you this,

50
00:03:07,487 --> 00:03:09,387
your mom's been
in a car accident.

51
00:03:11,591 --> 00:03:14,082
She's in the hospital.

52
00:03:14,160 --> 00:03:16,060
But she's got good doctors
taking care of her

53
00:03:16,129 --> 00:03:17,824
and I'm sure she's
going to be fine.

54
00:03:22,669 --> 00:03:24,034
Can I see her?

55
00:03:33,012 --> 00:03:34,502
Can I go in?

56
00:03:34,581 --> 00:03:36,276
Not yet, hon.

57
00:03:36,349 --> 00:03:37,839
They'll be moving her
to a regular room

58
00:03:37,917 --> 00:03:40,715
in a couple of days and you
can talk to her then, okay?

59
00:03:42,822 --> 00:03:46,724
Is she gonna be okay?

60
00:03:46,793 --> 00:03:48,590
She's going to
be fine.

61
00:03:50,863 --> 00:03:52,387
Come on, in you get.

62
00:03:55,501 --> 00:03:58,834
You know, Alex, we can visit
your mom as much as you want

63
00:03:58,905 --> 00:04:00,532
once she's out of
intensive care.

64
00:04:00,607 --> 00:04:02,632
Would you like that?

65
00:04:02,709 --> 00:04:04,768
Okay, good night.

66
00:04:04,844 --> 00:04:06,209
I'll see you
in the morning.

67
00:04:10,483 --> 00:04:11,643
Miss Carson?

68
00:04:11,718 --> 00:04:13,208
Yeah?

69
00:04:13,286 --> 00:04:15,846
Could you leave a light on,
please?

70
00:04:15,922 --> 00:04:17,719
Of course I can, honey.

71
00:04:21,527 --> 00:04:23,757
It's going to be okay, Alex,
you'll see.

72
00:04:31,871 --> 00:04:37,275
Okay, I bought some groceries,
made soup and casseroles;

73
00:04:37,343 --> 00:04:38,776
you won't have to cook
for a while.

74
00:04:38,845 --> 00:04:40,870
Oh, thanks, Ellen,
you've been so helpful,

75
00:04:40,947 --> 00:04:43,074
especially with Alex.

76
00:04:43,149 --> 00:04:44,548
Here, have a seat.

77
00:04:44,617 --> 00:04:46,380
All right.

78
00:04:50,657 --> 00:04:52,955
Would you like me to stay
with you and Alex tonight?

79
00:04:53,026 --> 00:04:54,015
No, we're fine.

80
00:04:54,093 --> 00:04:55,355
You sure?

81
00:04:55,428 --> 00:04:57,896
It's okay.

82
00:04:57,964 --> 00:05:00,228
You be a good boy and take
care of your mom.

83
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:01,790
I will.

84
00:05:04,137 --> 00:05:05,263
You know what?

85
00:05:05,338 --> 00:05:07,101
I'm going to make you
some tea before I go.

86
00:05:07,173 --> 00:05:08,105
Want to help me, Alex?

87
00:05:08,174 --> 00:05:09,937
- Sure.
- Okay.

88
00:05:24,691 --> 00:05:27,057
My mother suffered
a serious head injury

89
00:05:27,126 --> 00:05:30,823
from a car accident and
developed bipolar disorder.

90
00:05:30,897 --> 00:05:33,491
When she was on her medication,
she was able to work

91
00:05:33,566 --> 00:05:37,297
as a professor and things
were mostly normal.

92
00:05:37,370 --> 00:05:39,497
But the medication
had harsh side effects.

93
00:05:41,407 --> 00:05:44,035
The drugs made it harder
for her to think clearly.

94
00:05:44,110 --> 00:05:46,203
Mom, I'm home.

95
00:05:46,279 --> 00:05:49,874
She hated that so she
stopped taking them.

96
00:05:49,949 --> 00:05:50,973
Mom?

97
00:05:51,050 --> 00:05:52,847
Then she spiraled down,
couldn't work,

98
00:05:52,919 --> 00:05:54,978
and became neglectful
and abusive.

99
00:05:55,054 --> 00:05:56,715
Mom, I got my report card.

100
00:06:03,830 --> 00:06:06,492
Are you okay?

101
00:06:06,566 --> 00:06:09,160
I have a headache, Alex,
leave me alone.

102
00:06:11,371 --> 00:06:12,565
Okay.

103
00:06:16,509 --> 00:06:19,205
I'll leave it here so you
can sign it later.

104
00:06:39,298 --> 00:06:40,788
Have a seat, Alex.

105
00:06:45,138 --> 00:06:47,368
Your mom had to go back
to the hospital.

106
00:06:47,440 --> 00:06:48,304
What?

107
00:06:48,374 --> 00:06:49,432
What happened?

108
00:06:49,509 --> 00:06:51,773
She just had a little setback,

109
00:06:51,844 --> 00:06:53,937
but the doctors are taking
really good care of her

110
00:06:54,013 --> 00:06:56,311
and she'll be home
as soon as possible.

111
00:06:56,382 --> 00:06:58,907
Now this is Mrs. Edenger.

112
00:06:58,985 --> 00:06:59,974
Hi.

113
00:07:00,052 --> 00:07:02,145
Hello, Alex,
nice to meet you.

114
00:07:02,221 --> 00:07:03,848
Nice to meet you too.

115
00:07:03,923 --> 00:07:05,823
I'm from Child Protective
Services.

116
00:07:05,892 --> 00:07:07,723
Do you know what that is?

117
00:07:07,794 --> 00:07:10,627
Well, we find nice people
to take care of children

118
00:07:10,696 --> 00:07:12,493
when their parents can't.

119
00:07:14,734 --> 00:07:17,464
So while your mom
is in the hospital...

120
00:07:17,537 --> 00:07:19,664
you'll stay with a family
who live near here.

121
00:07:23,209 --> 00:07:24,938
Why can't I stay
with Miss Carson?

122
00:07:25,011 --> 00:07:26,205
Well, she won't be able
to take care of you

123
00:07:26,279 --> 00:07:27,974
for as long as your
mom is going to be

124
00:07:28,047 --> 00:07:29,105
in the hospital this time.

125
00:07:36,522 --> 00:07:38,456
See, this isn't so bad.

126
00:07:38,524 --> 00:07:40,321
Please don't make me
stay here.

127
00:07:40,393 --> 00:07:43,021
It's just for a few weeks, 'til
your mom gets better, okay?

128
00:07:43,095 --> 00:07:44,084
Please don't make me!

129
00:07:44,163 --> 00:07:46,996
Alex, I need you to be
a big boy.

130
00:07:47,066 --> 00:07:50,160
Let's just sit down
right here.

131
00:07:50,236 --> 00:07:54,263
I've got to go
and talk to your foster mom.

132
00:07:54,340 --> 00:07:56,308
Maybe you can unpack
your suitcase.

133
00:08:05,451 --> 00:08:08,784
I'll come check on you
sometime next week, okay?

134
00:08:11,924 --> 00:08:13,585
It's going to be okay, Alex.

135
00:08:24,470 --> 00:08:26,802
When my mother was
taken away from me

136
00:08:26,873 --> 00:08:29,637
I felt alone, abandoned,

137
00:08:29,709 --> 00:08:33,611
and I was terrified that I
would never see her again.

138
00:08:33,679 --> 00:08:35,237
I will never forget
the first time

139
00:08:35,314 --> 00:08:38,909
I was put in a strange home
with people I didn't know.

140
00:08:38,985 --> 00:08:41,044
Days felt like weeks,

141
00:08:41,120 --> 00:08:44,453
a month without my mom
felt like a lifetime.

142
00:08:44,524 --> 00:08:46,185
Mom!

143
00:08:48,394 --> 00:08:49,725
Please don't leave me
again, Mom.

144
00:08:49,795 --> 00:08:51,786
Please!

145
00:08:51,864 --> 00:08:54,298
I'll try not to.

146
00:08:54,367 --> 00:08:56,631
I'll do my best,
okay?

147
00:08:56,702 --> 00:08:59,899
There were times when my mother
returned from the hospital

148
00:08:59,972 --> 00:09:02,440
that I thought I had
my life back,

149
00:09:02,508 --> 00:09:04,703
but it never lasted for long.

150
00:09:04,777 --> 00:09:06,870
Mom, come on,
it's Christmas!

151
00:09:11,017 --> 00:09:13,212
Mom, come on!

152
00:09:13,286 --> 00:09:14,412
Mom!

153
00:09:17,256 --> 00:09:20,225
Mom?

154
00:09:20,293 --> 00:09:22,727
Can you leave me
alone please?

155
00:09:22,795 --> 00:09:25,389
But it's Christmas, Mom.

156
00:09:25,464 --> 00:09:27,659
I have a present
for you.

157
00:09:27,733 --> 00:09:29,394
I made it myself.

158
00:09:29,468 --> 00:09:30,628
Please not now.

159
00:09:39,245 --> 00:09:41,713
My mother struggled constantly
with the symptoms

160
00:09:41,781 --> 00:09:43,305
of her condition

161
00:09:43,382 --> 00:09:46,749
and the harsh side effects of
the drugs she had to take.

162
00:09:46,819 --> 00:09:49,049
Even when I was home
with my mom

163
00:09:49,121 --> 00:09:51,419
it often felt like she wasn't
really there.

164
00:10:04,470 --> 00:10:06,665
Mom.

165
00:10:06,739 --> 00:10:07,671
Mom?

166
00:10:07,740 --> 00:10:09,139
Can't you see I'm looking
for a job?

167
00:10:09,208 --> 00:10:11,438
I need some lunch money.

168
00:10:11,510 --> 00:10:13,444
Your lunch is supposed
to be free.

169
00:10:13,512 --> 00:10:16,675
You didn't fill out that paper
I brought home from school.

170
00:10:16,749 --> 00:10:18,649
I can't get free lunch
until you do that.

171
00:10:18,718 --> 00:10:19,844
I'll do it later.

172
00:10:19,919 --> 00:10:21,352
What about lunch today?

173
00:10:29,161 --> 00:10:29,923
There!

174
00:10:29,996 --> 00:10:31,088
That's all I can do!

175
00:10:31,163 --> 00:10:33,723
I don't have a job,
I don't have money!

176
00:10:43,309 --> 00:10:45,277
There was never enough money,

177
00:10:45,344 --> 00:10:47,676
and I always worried that
we'd have enough food

178
00:10:47,747 --> 00:10:50,238
or that my mom would be
able to pay our rent.

179
00:10:52,752 --> 00:10:55,812
It wasn't easy, but I learned
to fend for myself.

180
00:11:06,198 --> 00:11:07,324
Open this door!

181
00:11:07,400 --> 00:11:08,492
Do you hear me?

182
00:11:08,567 --> 00:11:10,000
This is what I get for taking
care of you

183
00:11:10,069 --> 00:11:12,799
and feeding you,
devoting my life to you?!

184
00:11:12,872 --> 00:11:13,998
I pay the rent here!

185
00:11:14,073 --> 00:11:16,132
You open this door
right now!

186
00:11:16,208 --> 00:11:17,505
I'm going to kick it in, Alex.

187
00:11:17,576 --> 00:11:19,009
If you don't open
this door right now

188
00:11:19,078 --> 00:11:20,807
you're going to be so sorry!

189
00:11:20,880 --> 00:11:21,642
Hey!

190
00:11:22,648 --> 00:11:24,616
Hey, what's going on
in there?

191
00:11:24,684 --> 00:11:25,946
What?

192
00:11:26,018 --> 00:11:28,714
Look, lady, how many times do
I have to come down here?

193
00:11:28,788 --> 00:11:31,655
If you don't keep it down,
I'm gonna call the police.

194
00:11:34,226 --> 00:11:37,252
You don't have to do this,
let me go back to my apartment.

195
00:11:37,329 --> 00:11:39,729
I'll... I'll calm down.

196
00:11:39,799 --> 00:11:41,460
I'll be fine, okay?

197
00:11:41,534 --> 00:11:43,832
Just let me...

198
00:11:43,903 --> 00:11:45,427
Please...

199
00:11:45,504 --> 00:11:46,562
I don't want to go.

200
00:11:46,639 --> 00:11:48,402
I... I... I can't do this.

201
00:11:48,474 --> 00:11:50,567
I'll be okay.

202
00:11:50,643 --> 00:11:54,443
Oh, there's my son,
don't put in front of him.

203
00:12:00,086 --> 00:12:03,283
My mother was taken away
from me many times.

204
00:12:03,355 --> 00:12:06,188
Sometimes my mom was
taken away for weeks,

205
00:12:06,258 --> 00:12:08,419
other times for months.

206
00:12:08,494 --> 00:12:11,156
She'd be hospitalized
and put on medication

207
00:12:11,230 --> 00:12:14,597
and I'd end up living
with strangers again.

208
00:12:14,667 --> 00:12:17,295
After a while,
she'd return to stability

209
00:12:17,369 --> 00:12:19,496
and I'd be placed
back in her care,

210
00:12:19,572 --> 00:12:21,062
but it always felt precarious.

211
00:12:24,310 --> 00:12:25,800
I lived in fear

212
00:12:25,878 --> 00:12:30,281
because I knew that a life with
my mother could never last.

213
00:12:30,349 --> 00:12:32,544
Before long,
she'd go off her medication

214
00:12:32,618 --> 00:12:35,485
and everything would
fall apart again.

215
00:12:36,889 --> 00:12:38,322
I felt bad for my mom

216
00:12:38,390 --> 00:12:40,654
because she couldn't
take care of herself

217
00:12:40,726 --> 00:12:42,660
let alone take care of me.

218
00:12:46,499 --> 00:12:47,989
When I was 16

219
00:12:48,067 --> 00:12:49,557
I left my latest foster home

220
00:12:49,635 --> 00:12:51,967
and returned to live
with my mother.

221
00:12:52,037 --> 00:12:54,835
Fortunately for me,
our apartment was located

222
00:12:54,907 --> 00:12:57,239
in the Eagle Creek
High School district,

223
00:12:57,309 --> 00:12:58,742
one of the best in the state.

224
00:13:08,854 --> 00:13:10,617
It wasn't easy
coming in as a junior

225
00:13:10,689 --> 00:13:13,283
after the semester
had already started.

226
00:13:15,928 --> 00:13:18,123
Your transcript is certainly
impressive, Alex.

227
00:13:18,197 --> 00:13:22,133
I mean, one point below
a perfect score on your ACT.

228
00:13:22,201 --> 00:13:23,862
Wow!

229
00:13:23,936 --> 00:13:26,404
I mean, considering how many
schools you've attended,

230
00:13:26,472 --> 00:13:29,498
your GPA is especially
remarkable.

231
00:13:29,575 --> 00:13:32,635
Yeah, I, ah, I moved a lot.

232
00:13:32,711 --> 00:13:34,235
Well, you keep this up and
you're well on your way

233
00:13:34,313 --> 00:13:36,247
to getting into a top school.

234
00:13:36,315 --> 00:13:38,010
Any idea where you'd
like to go?

235
00:13:38,083 --> 00:13:41,880
Harvard.

236
00:13:41,954 --> 00:13:45,947
Well, that's a lofty goal,
but one I think you can reach.

237
00:13:47,459 --> 00:13:49,427
Now, look, you're going to have
to keep up your grades.

238
00:13:49,495 --> 00:13:51,019
I will.

239
00:13:51,096 --> 00:13:53,257
I made a promise.

240
00:13:53,332 --> 00:13:55,527
Okay then.

241
00:13:55,601 --> 00:13:57,660
I'll do my best to help you
keep that promise.

242
00:14:01,240 --> 00:14:03,105
That needs to be
much better.

243
00:14:06,579 --> 00:14:08,740
This is a nice start.

244
00:14:14,553 --> 00:14:16,350
Exceptional work, Alex.

245
00:14:21,026 --> 00:14:23,017
- You need to buck up.
- He got an "A."

246
00:14:23,095 --> 00:14:25,893
All right, people, listen up.

247
00:14:25,965 --> 00:14:30,026
The midterm assignment for this
semester is a 50-page paper

248
00:14:30,102 --> 00:14:33,503
on an aspect about government
that you will choose.

249
00:14:34,874 --> 00:14:37,434
Okay, okay, don't worry.

250
00:14:37,509 --> 00:14:39,875
You can work in groups
of up to three people.

251
00:14:44,016 --> 00:14:47,645
Hey, new kid.

252
00:14:47,720 --> 00:14:49,620
Nice work in Rowe's class.

253
00:14:49,688 --> 00:14:52,486
- That guy never gives an "A."
- Yeah, it's like his thing.

254
00:14:52,558 --> 00:14:54,958
An "A" represents perfection,

255
00:14:55,027 --> 00:14:57,018
and I've never seen
a perfect paper.

256
00:14:57,096 --> 00:14:59,087
I'm Lucy, this is Danny.

257
00:14:59,164 --> 00:15:00,426
Alex.

258
00:15:00,499 --> 00:15:01,796
We were wondering
if you wanted to work

259
00:15:01,867 --> 00:15:03,596
on the midterm with us?

260
00:15:03,669 --> 00:15:04,863
Really?

261
00:15:04,937 --> 00:15:06,871
Yeah, I mean Danny here is
a straight "C" student

262
00:15:06,939 --> 00:15:08,065
so he'll be tons of help.

263
00:15:08,140 --> 00:15:09,801
Hey, you should
talk, Picasso.

264
00:15:09,875 --> 00:15:11,274
All she cares about
is art and poetry.

265
00:15:11,343 --> 00:15:13,277
Social studies isn't her thing.

266
00:15:13,345 --> 00:15:14,835
You can see what you'd be
getting yourself into.

267
00:15:14,914 --> 00:15:16,643
I mean, neither one
of us is a brain like you.

268
00:15:16,715 --> 00:15:19,377
Not a problem, when do
you want to start?

269
00:15:19,451 --> 00:15:22,045
Do you want to meet at my house
on Saturday, 10:00?

270
00:15:22,121 --> 00:15:23,145
10:00?

271
00:15:23,222 --> 00:15:25,190
You know I sleep 'til noon
on Saturday.

272
00:15:25,257 --> 00:15:26,383
Fine, 11:00.

273
00:15:26,458 --> 00:15:27,254
Alex?

274
00:15:27,326 --> 00:15:28,623
Sounds good.

275
00:15:28,694 --> 00:15:30,628
Okay, but I'm going to be in
a coma for the first hour.

276
00:15:30,696 --> 00:15:32,129
You're always in a coma.

277
00:15:33,332 --> 00:15:35,823
Eagle Creek High
became everything to me.

278
00:15:35,901 --> 00:15:37,869
I immersed myself in studies

279
00:15:37,937 --> 00:15:40,633
and found compassion and
support from my new friends.

280
00:15:43,042 --> 00:15:44,771
When chaos reigned at home,

281
00:15:44,843 --> 00:15:46,504
the school became
a refuge for me.

282
00:16:03,162 --> 00:16:04,390
Mom?

283
00:16:04,463 --> 00:16:05,225
What are you doing?

284
00:16:05,297 --> 00:16:06,730
I'm sick of these medications,

285
00:16:06,799 --> 00:16:08,790
the side effects are
making me worse!

286
00:16:08,867 --> 00:16:12,064
I can't focus,
my... my head is throbbing.

287
00:16:12,137 --> 00:16:13,570
- I can't think!
- Stop it.

288
00:16:13,639 --> 00:16:14,799
Please!

289
00:16:14,873 --> 00:16:16,306
- Mom!
- It hurts!

290
00:16:16,375 --> 00:16:17,933
But you know what happens
when you stop taking them!

291
00:16:18,010 --> 00:16:19,875
I don't care anymore!

292
00:16:53,645 --> 00:16:54,737
We really lucked out
with you, Alex,

293
00:16:54,813 --> 00:16:56,576
we might actually do
all right on this paper.

294
00:16:56,648 --> 00:16:58,047
We're going to get an "A."

295
00:16:58,117 --> 00:16:59,709
You sound pretty sure
of yourself.

296
00:16:59,785 --> 00:17:01,309
We have to.

297
00:17:01,387 --> 00:17:03,719
I've got to maintain a 4.0
to have any chance

298
00:17:03,789 --> 00:17:04,915
at getting into Harvard.

299
00:17:04,990 --> 00:17:06,184
Harvard?

300
00:17:06,258 --> 00:17:07,350
Right, and I'm going
to play shortstop

301
00:17:07,426 --> 00:17:08,825
for the Detroit Tigers.

302
00:17:08,894 --> 00:17:11,021
So you think
I'm delusional?

303
00:17:11,096 --> 00:17:11,858
Yeah.

304
00:17:11,930 --> 00:17:13,295
I don't.

305
00:17:13,365 --> 00:17:15,799
I'm 1,000% positive
you can do it.

306
00:17:24,076 --> 00:17:25,407
Mom?

307
00:17:25,477 --> 00:17:26,876
I'm home!

308
00:17:44,630 --> 00:17:46,495
Mom, there's no food!

309
00:18:38,383 --> 00:18:39,645
I'm gonna get going,

310
00:18:39,718 --> 00:18:42,050
my mom and I are going
to an art show.

311
00:18:43,355 --> 00:18:46,381
Whoa, check this out,
crazy lady, 9:00.

312
00:18:46,458 --> 00:18:47,823
Alex!

313
00:18:47,893 --> 00:18:49,417
What are you doing here?

314
00:18:49,495 --> 00:18:50,792
You should be home!

315
00:18:50,863 --> 00:18:51,921
I've been looking everywhere
for you!

316
00:18:51,997 --> 00:18:53,658
Why do I have to track
you down?

317
00:18:53,732 --> 00:18:55,927
I had to come all the way
over here, why?

318
00:18:56,001 --> 00:18:57,127
Calm down.

319
00:18:57,202 --> 00:18:58,726
You don't tell me what
classes you're taking

320
00:18:58,804 --> 00:19:00,271
or what you're doing
after school!

321
00:19:00,339 --> 00:19:01,237
Nothing!

322
00:19:01,306 --> 00:19:02,637
Mom, don't do this to me,
please!

323
00:19:02,708 --> 00:19:04,767
Don't you dare tell me what
to do, I'm your mother.

324
00:19:04,843 --> 00:19:06,470
You respect me!

325
00:19:06,545 --> 00:19:08,012
Ah, excuse me, Mrs. Nistor?

326
00:19:08,080 --> 00:19:10,344
Ah, did you stop by the office
and get a visitor's pass?

327
00:19:10,415 --> 00:19:11,404
What?

328
00:19:11,483 --> 00:19:12,472
No.

329
00:19:12,551 --> 00:19:15,384
I'm sorry,
it's school policy.

330
00:19:15,454 --> 00:19:17,115
Wanna come with me?

331
00:19:17,189 --> 00:19:18,713
You wanna come?

332
00:19:36,909 --> 00:19:38,206
Alex, wait!

333
00:19:38,277 --> 00:19:39,266
Leave me alone!

334
00:19:39,344 --> 00:19:41,437
Alex, please can
you talk to me?

335
00:19:41,513 --> 00:19:42,605
There's nothing
to talk about!

336
00:19:42,681 --> 00:19:45,514
My mom is crazy, okay?

337
00:19:45,584 --> 00:19:47,415
Well, what's wrong with her?

338
00:19:47,486 --> 00:19:51,183
Well, she's sick,
and she can't help it.

339
00:19:51,256 --> 00:19:54,987
We can't afford insurance so
she can't get good treatment.

340
00:19:55,060 --> 00:19:56,584
They hospitalize her
when it's a crisis

341
00:19:56,662 --> 00:19:58,926
and when she's on her own,
she just can't cope.

342
00:20:02,100 --> 00:20:04,625
If you knew what she
used to be like

343
00:20:04,703 --> 00:20:06,330
before she got sick...

344
00:20:07,906 --> 00:20:10,602
She has a PhD.

345
00:20:10,676 --> 00:20:14,407
It kills her when her mind
can't function the way it did.

346
00:20:15,647 --> 00:20:19,777
That must be really hard
for her, and you.

347
00:20:19,851 --> 00:20:21,375
I think I know what
you're going through.

348
00:20:21,453 --> 00:20:23,045
Oh, I doubt that.

349
00:20:24,690 --> 00:20:28,251
My father's a
recovering alcoholic.

350
00:20:28,327 --> 00:20:31,490
Before he got sober, he was
completely unpredictable.

351
00:20:31,563 --> 00:20:34,123
- Sorry, Lucy, I had no idea.
- It's okay, he's good.

352
00:20:34,199 --> 00:20:36,895
He's in a program and
he's doing really great.

353
00:20:36,969 --> 00:20:39,437
He's my dad again.

354
00:20:43,175 --> 00:20:45,541
What are you going to do
about your mom?

355
00:20:45,611 --> 00:20:47,044
I don't know.

356
00:20:47,112 --> 00:20:51,515
I mean, I want to save her,
but I don't know how.

357
00:20:53,785 --> 00:20:55,514
Sounds pretty stupid,
huh?

358
00:20:55,587 --> 00:20:57,919
No, it sounds heroic.

359
00:21:09,101 --> 00:21:10,432
What happened?

360
00:21:10,502 --> 00:21:12,936
I'm sorry, Alex, your mother
couldn't pay the rent.

361
00:21:13,005 --> 00:21:15,735
You've been evicted.

362
00:21:15,807 --> 00:21:18,298
- Where is she?
- Hospitalized.

363
00:21:18,377 --> 00:21:20,277
She went off her meds again!

364
00:21:20,345 --> 00:21:21,744
I told her she's got
to keep taking them

365
00:21:21,813 --> 00:21:22,973
but she won't listen.

366
00:21:23,048 --> 00:21:24,606
I found an emergency
foster home for you.

367
00:21:24,683 --> 00:21:26,116
Great, my fourth!

368
00:21:26,184 --> 00:21:28,084
Well, hopefully your mom will
stabilize in a couple of weeks.

369
00:21:28,153 --> 00:21:29,347
Aww, what's the point?

370
00:21:29,421 --> 00:21:30,513
She'll just go off her meds,
go crazy and wind up

371
00:21:30,589 --> 00:21:31,681
right back in the hospital!

372
00:21:31,757 --> 00:21:33,054
I understand how frustrated
you must be.

373
00:21:33,125 --> 00:21:34,854
- No, you don't!
- Yes, I do!

374
00:21:37,296 --> 00:21:38,854
Now, I've made arrangements
for someone to come

375
00:21:38,930 --> 00:21:42,058
and take these
into storage, okay?

376
00:21:42,134 --> 00:21:43,761
Just pick out a couple things
that you need

377
00:21:43,835 --> 00:21:46,360
and I will take you to
your foster placement.

378
00:21:53,111 --> 00:21:57,514
My mom was always being
taken away from me.

379
00:21:57,582 --> 00:22:00,244
And while my social worker
helped keep me fed,

380
00:22:00,319 --> 00:22:02,287
clothed and sheltered,

381
00:22:02,354 --> 00:22:06,154
the cycle of instability
started to take a toll.

382
00:22:09,161 --> 00:22:13,097
For six years I had been
in and out of foster homes,

383
00:22:13,165 --> 00:22:17,431
my mom in and out
of hospitals.

384
00:22:17,502 --> 00:22:20,437
I kept telling myself that
someday she'd get better,

385
00:22:20,505 --> 00:22:24,236
be like her old self again
and stay that way,

386
00:22:24,309 --> 00:22:27,039
but I finally had
to face reality;

387
00:22:27,112 --> 00:22:28,511
it just wasn't going
to happen.

388
00:22:31,249 --> 00:22:32,841
If anything was going
to change

389
00:22:32,918 --> 00:22:36,046
it would be up to me
to change it.

390
00:22:36,121 --> 00:22:38,851
I just, I can't take it
anymore.

391
00:22:38,924 --> 00:22:43,224
The depression, the rants,
the constant uncertainty.

392
00:22:43,295 --> 00:22:46,458
Nobody should have
to live like that.

393
00:22:46,531 --> 00:22:49,466
What exactly are you
asking, Alex?

394
00:22:49,534 --> 00:22:51,832
I'm asking to terminate
my mom's parental rights.

395
00:22:53,538 --> 00:22:57,065
I have the right do
that now, I'm 16.

396
00:22:57,142 --> 00:23:00,202
Do you fully understand
what that means?

397
00:23:00,278 --> 00:23:01,575
Means that I don't
have to be afraid

398
00:23:01,646 --> 00:23:03,307
of her hurting herself anymore.

399
00:23:03,382 --> 00:23:05,748
Or me.

400
00:23:05,817 --> 00:23:08,047
It doesn't mean
I don't love her.

401
00:23:12,624 --> 00:23:14,216
Let's begin.

402
00:23:14,292 --> 00:23:18,729
Alex, these attorneys are here
representing your mother.

403
00:23:18,797 --> 00:23:20,230
The court doesn't allow her
to be present

404
00:23:20,298 --> 00:23:21,663
during your testimony

405
00:23:21,733 --> 00:23:25,726
so that you may speak
freely and honestly.

406
00:23:25,804 --> 00:23:27,738
Do you understand?

407
00:23:29,708 --> 00:23:31,676
Very well, let's proceed.

408
00:23:31,743 --> 00:23:35,008
Alex, explain to Judge Brady
why it is

409
00:23:35,080 --> 00:23:38,049
you want your mother's
rights to be terminated.

410
00:23:40,986 --> 00:23:43,887
Please believe me,
Your Honor,

411
00:23:43,955 --> 00:23:47,755
this was the hardest decision
I've ever had to make.

412
00:23:47,826 --> 00:23:49,555
I love my mother;

413
00:23:49,628 --> 00:23:52,620
she was a role-model
for me when I was little.

414
00:23:52,697 --> 00:23:55,996
I got my curiosity and love
of learning from her.

415
00:23:56,067 --> 00:23:58,092
But she's a very
different person now

416
00:23:58,170 --> 00:24:02,197
and if I'm put back in her
custody, the circus will go on.

417
00:24:02,274 --> 00:24:03,502
The circus?

418
00:24:03,575 --> 00:24:06,703
The craziness.

419
00:24:06,778 --> 00:24:09,008
Being evicted
from our apartment,

420
00:24:09,080 --> 00:24:11,014
not having enough food,

421
00:24:11,082 --> 00:24:14,074
police being called by neighbors
because of her screaming,

422
00:24:14,152 --> 00:24:15,881
going in and out
of foster homes.

423
00:24:15,954 --> 00:24:20,823
Do you understand
what this means, legally?

424
00:24:20,892 --> 00:24:23,383
Yes, ma'am.

425
00:24:23,462 --> 00:24:26,954
It means that,
according to the law,

426
00:24:27,032 --> 00:24:28,499
I won't have a mother anymore.

427
00:24:51,156 --> 00:24:54,853
Alex... how could
you do this?

428
00:25:05,704 --> 00:25:08,264
I'm sorry, Mom.

429
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:39,528
Well, your mother's testimony
didn't help her case.

430
00:25:39,604 --> 00:25:43,370
The judge has granted
termination of parental rights.

431
00:25:43,441 --> 00:25:45,170
You won.

432
00:25:45,243 --> 00:25:47,404
No, I didn't.

433
00:25:47,479 --> 00:25:49,310
Nobody won.

434
00:26:01,059 --> 00:26:03,027
You're 16, Alex,

435
00:26:03,094 --> 00:26:08,555
finding a permanent placement
for a teenager, I'm sorry.

436
00:26:08,633 --> 00:26:10,931
You'll be living here now.

437
00:26:11,002 --> 00:26:12,162
What about school?

438
00:26:12,237 --> 00:26:13,636
Well, you can stay
at Eagle Creek.

439
00:26:13,705 --> 00:26:17,197
Umm, the orphanage has a driver
who will transport you

440
00:26:17,275 --> 00:26:20,938
and the school district
will reimburse them.

441
00:26:21,012 --> 00:26:23,276
So I guess it's official now.

442
00:26:23,348 --> 00:26:25,009
What?

443
00:26:25,083 --> 00:26:26,880
I don't have a family anymore.

444
00:26:42,467 --> 00:26:43,934
All right, here's an
information packet.

445
00:26:47,072 --> 00:26:50,007
As long as you accept all the
rules here, you'll do just fine.

446
00:26:50,075 --> 00:26:51,474
Rules?

447
00:26:51,543 --> 00:26:55,309
There's no fighting, no loud
music, lights out at 10:00.

448
00:26:55,380 --> 00:26:58,247
But I usually stay up
studying later than that.

449
00:26:58,316 --> 00:27:00,216
Well, you'll have to have your
homework done by 10:00.

450
00:27:00,285 --> 00:27:04,551
I have five or six hours
of homework a night.

451
00:27:04,623 --> 00:27:08,457
Well, we could possibly
make an exception.

452
00:27:08,526 --> 00:27:10,084
- Yes, sir.
- Okay.

453
00:27:11,329 --> 00:27:13,991
It says here we're not allowed
to have a checking account.

454
00:27:14,065 --> 00:27:15,225
That's correct.

455
00:27:15,300 --> 00:27:16,995
But I need mine so I have
a safe place to keep

456
00:27:17,068 --> 00:27:18,968
what I earn from my job
at the bookstore.

457
00:27:19,037 --> 00:27:21,028
No, no, no, no, you're not
allowed to have a job, son.

458
00:27:24,442 --> 00:27:27,934
I've never lived in an
institution like this before.

459
00:27:28,013 --> 00:27:30,777
This is different for me,
but maybe I'm different

460
00:27:30,849 --> 00:27:33,181
from the kids you're
used to dealing with.

461
00:27:33,251 --> 00:27:35,185
I work hard and
I'm highly motivated,

462
00:27:35,253 --> 00:27:37,619
I'm saving money
for college.

463
00:27:37,689 --> 00:27:39,020
Don't you want kids
to come out of here

464
00:27:39,090 --> 00:27:40,455
and go on to make something
of themselves?

465
00:27:40,525 --> 00:27:43,858
That's what
I'm trying to do.

466
00:27:43,928 --> 00:27:47,091
All right, but that does
not mean you are free

467
00:27:47,165 --> 00:27:49,531
to come and go as you please.

468
00:27:49,601 --> 00:27:51,535
Okay.

469
00:27:51,603 --> 00:27:54,128
Oh, one more thing, do
you have a cell phone?

470
00:27:54,205 --> 00:27:55,502
Yes, sir.

471
00:27:55,573 --> 00:27:58,508
All right, hand it over, you're
not allowed to keep that.

472
00:27:58,576 --> 00:28:00,737
But I won't be able to stay
in touch with my friends.

473
00:28:00,812 --> 00:28:03,975
Well, it's a security issue.

474
00:28:04,049 --> 00:28:05,448
Phone please.

475
00:28:25,770 --> 00:28:27,294
Hi.

476
00:28:29,774 --> 00:28:31,401
I'm Alex Chivescu.

477
00:28:31,476 --> 00:28:32,602
What kind of name is that?

478
00:28:32,677 --> 00:28:34,440
Romanian.

479
00:28:34,512 --> 00:28:39,108
But I was born here
so I'm American.

480
00:28:39,184 --> 00:28:41,209
Yeah, I was born here too,

481
00:28:41,286 --> 00:28:43,311
people still call me Mexican.

482
00:29:03,408 --> 00:29:05,842
Hey, hop in, Alex.

483
00:29:05,910 --> 00:29:07,275
How do you know
my name?

484
00:29:07,345 --> 00:29:09,472
Oh, I've heard all about you.

485
00:29:09,547 --> 00:29:11,606
- You have?
- Hmm, let's just say

486
00:29:11,683 --> 00:29:13,844
you don't exactly fit
the profile around here,

487
00:29:13,918 --> 00:29:15,613
you know what I'm saying?

488
00:29:19,791 --> 00:29:22,555
Listen, this is a long drive
to Eagle Creek.

489
00:29:22,627 --> 00:29:24,595
Why don't you hop up front
here with me?

490
00:29:28,299 --> 00:29:30,767
All right, buckle up,
my man.

491
00:29:36,141 --> 00:29:38,006
By the way, I'm Henry.

492
00:29:44,849 --> 00:29:46,282
Can you let me out here?

493
00:29:46,351 --> 00:29:47,818
Well, we're not
at your school yet.

494
00:29:47,886 --> 00:29:49,581
That's okay,
this is good.

495
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:05,201
Your friends don't know
where you're living, do they?

496
00:30:05,270 --> 00:30:06,862
No.

497
00:30:10,175 --> 00:30:13,144
Okay, well, I'll pick you back
up here after then.

498
00:30:13,211 --> 00:30:15,702
That would be great,
can you come at 5:00?

499
00:30:15,780 --> 00:30:17,077
Sure thing,
5:00 it is.

500
00:30:17,148 --> 00:30:18,445
Thanks, Henry.

501
00:30:26,257 --> 00:30:27,121
Wooo!

502
00:30:27,192 --> 00:30:29,490
Check it out,
we got an "A."

503
00:30:29,561 --> 00:30:31,051
That's capital "A," baby!

504
00:30:31,129 --> 00:30:32,687
Thanks to Alex.

505
00:30:32,764 --> 00:30:33,958
We should celebrate.

506
00:30:34,032 --> 00:30:35,897
Do you guys want to come
to my house and order pizza?

507
00:30:35,967 --> 00:30:36,899
I can't.

508
00:30:36,968 --> 00:30:39,801
I have something to do.

509
00:30:39,871 --> 00:30:41,566
I'll catch you
guys later.

510
00:30:41,639 --> 00:30:43,834
Later, dude.

511
00:30:43,908 --> 00:30:47,241
Ahh, my first "A"!

512
00:30:47,312 --> 00:30:48,438
I love that guy.

513
00:30:48,513 --> 00:30:49,775
Oh, my God.

514
00:30:55,854 --> 00:30:58,118
Hey, Henry, thanks
for picking me up.

515
00:31:10,101 --> 00:31:11,762
It's so stupid!

516
00:31:11,836 --> 00:31:13,133
I hate this crap.

517
00:31:13,204 --> 00:31:15,069
I mean, who cares
about "X"s and "Y"s?

518
00:31:15,139 --> 00:31:16,834
What's the point?

519
00:31:19,277 --> 00:31:21,404
You know, it's really not that
hard once you get the basics.

520
00:31:21,479 --> 00:31:23,572
Yeah, well, I'm never
gonna get it!

521
00:31:26,851 --> 00:31:29,183
What, you win all these?

522
00:31:29,254 --> 00:31:31,085
Yeah.

523
00:31:31,155 --> 00:31:32,918
What's this one for?

524
00:31:32,991 --> 00:31:35,289
It's a National Merit
Scholarship.

525
00:31:35,360 --> 00:31:36,691
And what's that?

526
00:31:36,761 --> 00:31:40,253
